JOHANNESBURG - General Motors is set to retrench close to 600 workers by July following last week s announcement that the company is leaving South Africa.The National Union of Mineworkers of South Africa (Numsa) has confirmed General Motor s notice of retrenchment.The union met with the management of General Motors on Monday.READ: Numsa shocked by GM exitThe 600 workers will be retrenched out of a workforce of 1,500 people.Numsa is concerned that these workers will struggle to find employment after the retrenchment.They are calling on workers to attend a general meeting in New Brighton in Port Elizabeth on Tuesday where they will discuss the issue in detail.eNCA